What do the variables represent?¶

Age - age of the patient

Sex - gender of the patient (0 = female; 1 = male)

cp - type of chest pain from 0 to 3. Value 0: typical angina Value 1: atypical angina Value 2: non-anginal pain Value 3: asymptomatic

trtbps - resting blood pressure measured in mmHg

chol - cholesterol levels in mg/dL measured by BMI sensor

fbs - fasting blood sugar > 120 mg/dl (1 = true; 0 = false)

restecg - resting ECG results (1 = abnormal; 0 = normal)

thalachh - maximum heart rate

exng - exercise induced angina (1 = yes; 0 = no)

oldpeak - measurement used in exercise stress testing to evaluate the extent of ST segment depression observed on an electrocardiogram (ECG or EKG). higher values mean reduced blood flow to muscle aka ischemia (0.0 - 1.0 is normal risk, 1.0 - 2.0 is moderate risk, 2.0 and above is high risk)

slp - slope of ST depression (0 = less indicative of ischemia; 1 = borderline or equivocal changes; 2 = more suggestive of ischemia especially if occurs during exercise stress testing)

caa - number of major vessels (0 - 3)

thall - thal rate (0 = normal; 1 = reduced blood flow to heart in specific area; 2 = reduced blood flow to heart in certain areas when exercising but at rest normal; 3 = normal or indeterminate results)

output - occurrence of heart attack (0 = no heart attack; 1 = heart attack)

What the means of trtbps and cholesterol tell us about the dataset¶

The mean of trtbps (systolic resting blood pressure) and mean of cholesterol in this dataset show us that most of the patients in this data set had high trtbps and cholesterol. As measured by the American Heart Association (AHA), a trtbps of less than 120 mmHg is normal, 120-129 elevated, 130-139 hypertension stage 1, 140 and higher hypertension stage 2. Furthermore, the AHA identifies a cholesterol of less than 200 mg/dL as desirable, 200-239 borderline high, 240 and above as high. According to these standards, the patients in this dataset have, on average, hypertension stage 1 and very high cholesterol levels. Although this could be relative to the fact that the mean age of the dataset is 54, the two are still very high.

for col in df_corr.columns:
    smallest = df_corr[col].nsmallest(2)
    smallest_name = smallest.index[-1]
    smallest_corr = smallest.iloc[-1]
    small = (smallest_name, smallest_corr)
    
    largest = df_corr[col].nlargest(2)
    largest_name = largest.index[1]
    largest_corr = largest.iloc[1]
    large = (largest_name, largest_corr)
    
    if abs(smallest_corr) > largest_corr:
        strongest = small
    else:
        strongest = large
    
    print(f'{col} has strongest correlation of {strongest[1]} with {strongest[0]}\n')

Hypothesis Testing Discrete Variables¶

Null Hypothesis:¶

The type of chest pain has no relevance someone having a heart attack

Alternate Hypothesis:¶

The type of chest pain has strong relevance to someone having a heart attack.

In [10]:
from scipy.stats import f_oneway

anova_cp = [df[df['cp'] == i]['output'] for i in df['cp'].unique()]

f_oneway(*anova_cp)
Out[10]:
F_onewayResult(statistic=np.float64(36.786781108607016), pvalue=np.float64(2.904720783531748e-20))

Observation:¶

The type of chest pain has a strong impact on if someone has a heart attack. The statistic of about 36.787 represents the variance between the means of output of different groups. Since it is a high statistic, it shows that there is a large difference in someone having a heart attack depending on what type of chest pain they are having. The pvalue which is 2.9e-20 is extremely low which shows significant results where we reject the null. This means that the type of chest pain does have a relevance to someone having a heart attack.

Below, we show that this is an accurate description. People that had a chest pain of type 0 (typical angina) were much more likely to have an output of no heart attack while people with types 1 or 2 which represent atypical angina and non-anginal pain respectively had a higher likelihood of having a heart attack.

Null Hypothesis:¶

The occurrence of exercise-induced angina does not have any impact on the occurrence of a heart attack.

Alternate Hypothesis:¶

The occurrence of exercise-induced angina has a strong impact on the occurrence of a heart attack.

In [403]:
anova_exng = [df[df['exng'] == i]['output'] for i in df['exng'].unique()]

f_oneway(*anova_exng)
Out[403]:
F_onewayResult(statistic=np.float64(70.95243821639592), pvalue=np.float64(1.520813838331386e-15))

Observation:¶

The occurrence of exercise-induced angina has a strong impact on the occurrence of a heart attack. As shown above, the anova test resulted in a statistic of about 70.95 which shows a strong variance between the means of output dependent on if someone had exng or not. The pvalue of 1.5e-15 shows that these results are significant so we reject the null.

As shown below, we see the histogram that was previously displayed that indicates people that did not have exng were more likely to have a heart attack than not. The reverse is true for those with exng.

Using these observations above on exng and cp along with some knowledge of the dataset and what these 2 variables mean, I decided to see if there was a relationship between exng and cp having an impact on output. This was because exercise-induced angina is generally identified as typical angina and, as such, the absence of it could mean that it is classified as other types of chest pain such as atypical angina, non-anginal pain, or asymptomatic. For example, for an exng of 0, which means that the angina is either not present or not exercise-induced, I looked to see if having chest pain that was not type 3 meant a higher likelihood of having a heart attack.

As seen below, this was undoubtedly the case. As such, I also tested to see if exng of 1 but different types of chest pain had a higher relevance to if a patient had a heart attack. In this analysis it is seen that people with exng of 1 were mostly classified has having a chest pain of type 0, which is accurate in relation to the description of the two variables. There were not many data points that had the other chest pain type classifications if they had exng of 1 and those that did had a slightly higher likelihood of experiencing a heart attack.

Hypothesis Testing Continuous Variables¶

Null Hypothesis:¶

The mean thalachh (maximum heart rate achieved) will not be different between the group that has the occurrence of a heart attack and the group that does not.

Alternate Hypothesis:¶

The mean thalachh will be different between the group that has the occurrence of a heart attack and the group that does not.

In [16]:
from scipy.stats import ttest_ind

thalachh_0 = df[df['output'] == 0]['thalachh']
thalachh_1 = df[df['output'] == 1]['thalachh']

ttest_ind(thalachh_0, thalachh_1)
Out[16]:
TtestResult(statistic=np.float64(-8.069702869452568), pvalue=np.float64(1.697337638656049e-14), df=np.float64(301.0))

Observation:¶

The t-test performed for thalachh above shows a statistic of -8 and pvalue of 1.7e-14. This means that the first group which is no heart attack has a much lower mean thalachh than that of the group which has a heart attack. The low pvalue makes this result significant and as such we reject the null.

This observation is clear when looking at the histogram below which shows that people with higher thalachh experience heart attacks at a much higher likelihood. The mean for both is shown below as well.

Null Hypothesis:¶

The mean oldpeak will not be different between the group that has the occurrence of a heart attack and the group that does not.

Alternate Hypothesis:¶

The mean oldpeak will be different between the group that has the occurrence of a heart attack and the group that does not.

In [407]:
oldpeak_0 = df[df['output'] == 0]['oldpeak']
oldpeak_1 = df[df['output'] == 1]['oldpeak']

ttest_ind(oldpeak_0, oldpeak_1)
Out[407]:
TtestResult(statistic=np.float64(8.279579663866222), pvalue=np.float64(4.085346391354627e-15), df=np.float64(301.0))

Observations:¶

As we can see above, the t-test performed is very significant with a pvalue of 4.09e-15. As such, we reject the null and say that the mean oldpeak will be different between the group that has the occurrence of a heart attack and the group that does not.

If we look at the histogram below, we can see that this is very true due to the fact that there is a large amount of people that have an oldpeak between 0 and 1 that have a heart attack. As such, the mean oldpeak for those with no heart attack is much higher than that of people that do not have a heart attack. However, we must perform another test as the accuracy of a classifier would not be high if we simply identified everybody with an oldpeak between 0 and 1 as having a heart attack and not having a heart attack otherwise.

Using data from above¶

When looking at the oldpeak graph it is clear that the risk of heart attack is only higher or around the same when oldpeak is between 0 and 1. As such, I utilize these observations to see if we can get a more significant test result by creating a categorical variable on if oldpeak is greater than or equal to 1 and if oldpeak is less than 1. I then test for significance between thalachh and output through these split groups.

Null Hypothesis:¶

(1) Patients with an oldpeak of less than 1.0 will not have a differing mean thalachh between the group within this that has a heart attack and the group that does not have a heart attack.

(2) Patients with an oldpeak of greater than or equal to 1.0 will not have a differing mean thalachh between the group within this that has a heart attack and the group that does not have a heart attack.

Alternate Hypothesis:¶

(1) Patients with an oldpeak of less than 1.0 will have a differing mean thalachh between the group within this that has a heart attack and the group that does not have a heart attack.

(2) Patients with an oldpeak of greater than or equal to 1.0 will have a differing mean thalachh between the group within this that has a heart attack and the group that does not have a heart attack.

colors = [sns.color_palette("bright")[4], sns.color_palette("Dark2")[0]]

true_group0 = op_thalac_temp_true[op_thalac_temp_true['output'] == 0]['thalachh']

plt.xlabel('thalachh (Maximum Heart Rate)')

ttest_ind(false_group0, false_group1)
Out[418]:
TtestResult(statistic=np.float64(-3.2863115267329768), pvalue=np.float64(0.0012415580616499135), df=np.float64(164.0))

Observations:¶

Although the significance level is not as low as the previous tests done, it could be seen as a more helpful test as it takes two different columns in the dataset and shows that a relation can be made between them in order to more accurately determine if someone will be more likely to have a heart attack or not. Furthermore, this test shows that it is significant for both as the pvalue is less than the acceptance of p < 0.05. As such, we reject both nulls.

If we just look at one column and classify people based on that, the accuracy of our predictions will be incredibly low. However, if we perform tests to determine a significance in the differing impact on the occurrence of a heart attack by looking at multiple variables, we can create a more accurate classifier.

Observations:¶

Due to the value counts of males being higher in this dataset, it has a stronger impact on the original df correlations. As such, it makes more sense to split the dataframes by sex and make the predictions based on if the new data point has sex 0 or sex 1.

An example is that thalachh has a much stronger impact on the prediction on if a male would have a heart attack compared to the prediction on if a female would have a heart attack. The correlation between output and thalachh for males is 0.42 while the correlation for females is merely 0.25.

When realizing this, it could be possible that we could create a classifier that combines a decision tree and a form of regression to be able to first split the data point into certain groups and perform tests that would lead to different probabilities on if the patient is going to have a heart attack or not.

# using male and female datasets separately

features_male = ['age', 'cp', 'oldpeak', 'thalachh']
target = 'output'


temp_male = male.copy()
no_outliers_male = temp_male[(np.abs(zscore(temp_male)) < 3).all(axis=1)]



X_male = no_outliers_male[features_male]
y_male = no_outliers_male[target]

X_train_male, X_test_male, y_train_male, y_test_male = train_test_split(
                                                                        X_male,
                                                                        y_male,
                                                                        test_size=0.2,
                                                                        random_state=42
                                                                        )

preproc = ColumnTransformer(
    transformers=[
        ('quantiles', QuantileTransformer(), ['age'])
    ],
    remainder='passthrough'
)

# Define the pipeline
pipeline = Pipeline([
    ('preprocessor', preproc),
    ('classifier', LogisticRegression())
])

param_grid = {
    'preprocessor__quantiles__n_quantiles': [i+1 for i in range(30)],
}

grid_search = GridSearchCV(pipeline, param_grid, cv=5, scoring='accuracy')

grid_search.fit(X_train_male, y_train_male)

best_param = grid_search.best_params_['preprocessor__quantiles__n_quantiles']
best_score = grid_search.best_score_

print(f"Best n_quantile: {best_param}")
print(f"Best cross-validation accuracy: {best_score}")

best_model = grid_search.best_estimator_
y_pred_male = best_model.predict(X_test_male)

print("Test set evaluation:")
print(classification_report(y_test_male, y_pred_male))


# As we can see, the accuracy for this model is not bad

Summary of above 2 models¶

As shown above, utilizing every feature in the male df allows us to get a mean cv score of 81.5 percent with f1-scores of 0.80 for no heart attack and 0.81 for heart attack. Meanwhile, utilizing every feature in the female df allows us to get a mean cv score of 90.5 percent with f1-score of 0.50 for no heart attack and 0.94 for heart attack. An issue with this model is seen in the female predictions as there is not enough data for females that do not have a heart attack and as such it could be more accurate for the model to simply predict heart attack all the time. As such, I attempt to create a model that mitigates this by using many but not all of the features in the female dataset below.

Best model for female dataset¶

As seen below, the best model for the female dataset uses multiple features and is much different from that of the male dataset. After messing with the features a lot by trying multiple combinations and seeing what might improve accuracy or the f1-score, it seems as though the best f1-score the model on classifying if females have a heart attack has a max f1-score of 0.50 for output no heart attack. This is most likely due to the lack of data on patients that are female and have a label under output as 0 which means the only way to make this model better is through finding more data on female patients that have an output of 0 and training the model on that data. This can allow for better f1-scores which emans the model will generalize well to unseen data and will be able to accurately predict if someone has a high likelihood for a heart attack or not. However, by adding some more features we were able to make the model have an average kfold cross-validation score of 91.8 percent over 5 folds.

Using original df without separating based on sex¶

According to the above, it could actually be better to just work with the original df and use sex as a feature instead of splitting it into male and female, although I believe this could also be because of the fact that females are a minimal part of the dataset compared to males. Furthermore, the cv score of the female dataset is higher than in this model using the entire dataset most likely due to the fact that the correlations of the female dataset is much different to that of the original df. The main takeaway is that the model should be split up into male and female datasets but more data should be obtained for the female dataset such that the model is able to also accurately identify if someone is more likely to not have a heart attack. Furthermore, quantile transforming the age with a quantile of 4 for the female dataset and 3 for the full dataset seems to optimize the cv score. The usage of age in the male dataset actually decreases the accuracy when more quantiles are input and has a better effect when age is ignored.
